VP Leni Robredo promised a transparent government that is led by an on-the-job president. (1/2)

#Blueprint2022

Dr. Jose Montemayor Jr. calls for multi-sectoral pandemic recovery—criticizing fellow candidates’ platforms in promoting direct action for the people.

He argues against national debt, advocating for government reform to acquire funds from budget leakages.

#Blueprint2022

Businessman Faisal Mangondato advocated for a governmental shift to federalism, which he claimed would solve corruption and poverty. He voted in favor of divorce as well as a non-neutral stance on the Russo-Ukrainian conflict.

#Blueprint2022

Senator Ping Lacson’s platform prioritizes anti-corruption reform, public-private partnerships in infrastructure projects, and balanced budgeting. He is in favor of same-sex civil unions and condemns Russia’s militaristic incursions into Ukraine. 

#Blueprint2022

Former Defense Chief Norberto Gonzales reiterated his vision of a “First World” Philippines. (1/2) 

#Blueprint2022

Labor Leader Leody De Guzman proposed a labor-first policy as well as national industrialization. This program will entail protectionist trade policies, increasing minimum wages to Php 750 per day, and making the health and education sectors public properties.

#Blueprint2022

Former Senator Bongbong Marcos refused to attend the debate, citing prior campaign commitments. Meanwhile, candidates who were present such as Robredo and Domagoso expressed that debate attendance is a sign of respect to the voting population.

#Blueprint2022
